Ensemble Techniques Project Solution¶

PART A¶

• DOMAIN: Telecom

• CONTEXT: A telecom company wants to use their historical customer data to predict behaviour to retain customers. You can analyse all relevant customer data and develop focused customer retention programs.

• DATA DESCRIPTION: Each row represents a customer, each column contains customer’s attributes described on the column Metadata. The data set includes information about:

  • Customers who left within the last month – the column is called Churn
  • Services that each customer has signed up for – phone, multiple lines, internet, online security, online backup, device protection, tech support, and streaming TV and movies
  • Customer account information – how long they’ve been a customer, contract, payment method, paperless billing, monthly charges, and total charges
  • Demographic info about customers – gender, age range, and if they have partners and dependents

• PROJECT OBJECTIVE: To Build a model that will help to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability to churn. This helps the company to understand the pinpoints and patterns of customer churn and will increase the focus on strategizing customer retention.

C. Create a function that will accept a DataFrame as input and return pie-charts for all the appropriate Categorical features. Clearly show percentage distribution in the pie-chart.

In [23]:
import math
from matplotlib.gridspec import GridSpec
# The function returns pie-charts for all the appropriate Categorical features of a data frame. 
# Input : Dataframe(df) 
# Output: Plots pie charts for all categorical features.

def display_pie_charts_for_Cat_features(df):
    # List all the categorical column names in variable 'categorical_features'
    categorical_features = df.select_dtypes(['object','category']).columns.to_list()

    # Skip Customer ID column as it is not needed
    categorical_features.remove('customerID')

    # Derive the num of rows required for subplot display. Assume num of col in grid is 3.
    ncol = len(categorical_features)
    nrow = math.ceil(ncol/3)

    # Set the Color Map for Pie Chart 
    cmap = plt.cm.prism
    cmap = plt.get_cmap('Accent')
    my_colors = [cmap(i) for i in np.linspace(0, 1, 8)]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 30))
    
    # Counter to point at the location in grid 
    count = 1

    for i in categorical_features:
      plt.subplot(nrow, 3, count)
      axes = df[i].value_counts().plot(kind ='pie', autopct='%1.1f%%',fontsize=12, colors = my_colors, wedgeprops = { 'linewidth' : 3, 'edgecolor' : 'white' })
      axes.set_ylabel('')
      axes.set_title(i.upper(),fontsize=20)
      count += 1

    fig.tight_layout(pad=5.0)
    plt.show();

#import Label Encoder
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
le = LabelEncoder()

# Define an array to store non-binary columns
nonBinaryCol = [] 

for col in telecom_df.columns:
    if (telecom_df[col].dtype == object):
        if (telecom_df[col].nunique() == 2):
            # Apply Label Encoder
            telecom_df[col] = le.fit_transform(telecom_df[col]) 
        else:
            nonBinaryCol.append(col)

# Skip CustomerID column for encoding
nonBinaryCol.remove('customerID')

# Now apply # One Hot Encoding for columns that are not binary.
telecom_df = pd.get_dummies(data = telecom_df, columns = nonBinaryCol)

X_train, y_train = X_smote, y_smote

# Data reading
def read_data(df):
  print(20*"-" + "Information".center(20) + 20*"-")
  print(df.info())
  print(20*"-" + "Data Shape".center(20) + 20*"-")
  print(df.shape)
  print("\n" + 20*"-" + "Sample Data".center(20) + 20*"-")
  print(df.head())
  print("\n" + 40 * "-" + "Describe the Data".center(40) + 40 * "-")
  print(df.describe([0.01, 0.05, 0.10, 0.50, 0.75, 0.90, 0.95, 0.99]).T)

def handle_missing_val(df_copy):
  # “TotalCharges” column has the data type “object,” but it should be a numeric column. Convert
  df_copy['TotalCharges'] = pd.to_numeric(df_copy['TotalCharges'], errors = 'coerce')

  # Check Missing Values
  df_copy.isnull().sum()

  # Drop the null values
  df_copy.dropna(inplace=True)

  # Verify that no NULL values exist
  df_copy.isnull().sum()

# Dropping ALL duplicate values
def handle_dup_val(df_copy):
  df_copy.drop_duplicates(subset="customerID", keep=False, inplace=True)

# Data cleaning 
def clean_data(df_copy):

  # Remove (automatic) from payment method values for easy data handling
  df_copy['PaymentMethod'] = df_copy['PaymentMethod'].str.replace('(automatic)', '', regex = False)

  # Divide customers into bins based on tenure. Get the max tenure
  print(df_copy['tenure'].max())
  
  # Here we will try to group the tenures 
  labels = ["{0} - {1}".format(i, i + 11) for i in range(1, 72, 12)]
  df_copy['tenure_group'] = pd.cut(df_copy.tenure, range(1, 80, 12), right=False, labels=labels)

  print(df_copy['tenure_group'].value_counts())

  # Data Type conversion where needed
  print(df_copy.describe().T)

  # Numerical columns of Interest: monthly charges, total charges
  df_copy['TotalCharges'] = df_copy['TotalCharges'].astype('float')
  df_copy['TotalCharges'] = df_copy['MonthlyCharges'].astype('float')

# Drop Unwanted features
def drop_unwanted_feat(df_copy):
  # Drop column tenure. 
  # CustomerID is needed to make Prabability analysis later
  df_copy.drop(columns = ['tenure'], axis=1, inplace=True)
  
  print("\n\n" + 20*"-" + "Information".center(20) + 20*"-")
  print(df_copy.info())
  print('-'*80)

# Function to preprocess the data
def preprocess_data(dataframe):

  # Data Reading
  read_data(dataframe)

  # Make a copy of the data to preprocess it further.
  df_copy = copy_dataframe(dataframe)

  # Impute missing values
  handle_missing_val(df_copy)

  # Impute duplicate values
  handle_dup_val(df_copy)

  # Data cleaning 
  clean_data(df_copy)

  # Dropping unnecessary features
  drop_unwanted_feat(df_copy)

  return df_copy

# The function returns pie-charts for all the appropriate Categorical features of a data frame. 
# Input : Dataframe(df) 
# Output: Plots pie charts for all categorical features.

def display_pie_charts_for_Cat_features(df):
    # List all the categorical column names in variable 'categorical_features'
    categorical_features = df.select_dtypes(['object','category']).columns.to_list()

    # Skip Customer ID column as it is not needed
    categorical_features.remove('customerID')

    # Derive the num of rows required for subplot display. Assume num of col in grid is 3.
    ncol = len(categorical_features)
    nrow = math.ceil(ncol/3)

    # Set the Color Map for Pie Chart 
    cmap = plt.cm.prism
    cmap = plt.get_cmap('Accent')
    my_colors = [cmap(i) for i in np.linspace(0, 1, 8)]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 30))
    
    # Counter to point at the location in grid 
    count = 1

    for i in categorical_features:
      plt.subplot(nrow, 3, count)
      axes = df[i].value_counts().plot(kind ='pie', autopct='%1.1f%%',fontsize=12, colors = my_colors, wedgeprops = { 'linewidth' : 3, 'edgecolor' : 'white' })
      axes.set_ylabel('')
      axes.set_title(i.upper(),fontsize=20)
      count += 1

    fig.tight_layout(pad=5.0)
    plt.show();

  display_pie_charts_for_Cat_features(df)

################################################# DATA ENCODING #########################################
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

def grab_col_names(df, cat_th=10, car_th=20):

  """
  It gives the names of categorical, numerical and categorical but cardinal variables in the data set.
  Note: Categorical variables with numerical appearance are also included in categorical variables.

  Parameters:
  -----------
  df    : Dataframe      (The dataframe from which variable names are to be retrieved)
  cat_th: int, optional  (threshold value for numeric but categorical variables)
  car_th: int, optinal   (threshold value for categorical but cardinal variables)

  Returns:
  --------
  cat_cols: list         (Categorical variable list)
  num_cols: list         (Numeric variable list)
  cat_but_car: list      (Categorical but cardinal variable list)

  Notes: 
  ------
  cat_cols + num_cols + cat_but_car = total number of variables
  num_but_cat is inside cat_cols.
  The sum of the 3 returned lists equals the total number of variables: 
  cat_cols + num_cols + cat_but_car = number of variables
  """
  # cat_cols, cat_but_car
  cat_cols    = [col for col in df.columns if df[col].dtypes == "O"]
  num_but_cat = [col for col in df.columns if df[col].nunique() < cat_th and df[col].dtypes != "O"]
  cat_but_car = [col for col in df.columns if df[col].nunique() > car_th and df[col].dtypes == "O"]
  cat_cols    = cat_cols + num_but_cat
  cat_cols    = [col for col in cat_cols if col not in cat_but_car]

  # num_cols
  num_cols    = [col for col in df.columns if df[col].dtypes != "O"]
  num_cols    = [col for col in num_cols if col not in num_but_cat]

  return cat_cols, num_cols, cat_but_car

def outlier_thresholds(df, col_name, q1=0.05, q3=0.95):
    quartile1 = df[col_name].quantile(q1)
    quartile3 = df[col_name].quantile(q3)
    interquantile_range = quartile3 - quartile1
    up_limit = quartile3 + 1.5 * interquantile_range
    low_limit = quartile1 - 1.5 * interquantile_range
    return low_limit, up_limit

def check_outlier(df, col_name):
    low_limit, up_limit = outlier_thresholds(df, col_name)
    if (df[(df[col_name] > up_limit) | (df[col_name] < low_limit)].any(axis=None)):
        return True
    else:
        return False

def grab_outliers(df, col_name, index=False):
    low, up = outlier_thresholds(df, col_name)

    if (df[((df[col_name] < low) | (df[col_name] > up))].shape[0] > 10):
        print(df[((df[col_name] < low) | (df[col_name] > up))].head())
    else:
        print(df[((df[col_name] < low) | (df[col_name] > up))])

    if index:
        outlier_index = df[((df[col_name] < low) | (df[col_name] > up))].index
        return outlier_index

def encode_cat_var(df, cat_cols):
  '''
    Apply Label Encoder to categorical features which are binary
    Apply get_dummies() to categorical features which have multiple values
  '''
  # import Label Encoder
  le = LabelEncoder()

  # Define an array to store non-binary columns
  nonBinaryCol = [] 

  for col in cat_cols:
    if (df[col].nunique() == 2):
        # Apply Label Encoder
        df[col] = le.fit_transform(df[col]) 
    else:
        nonBinaryCol.append(col)

  # Now apply One Hot Encoding for columns that are not binary.
  df = pd.get_dummies(data = df, columns = nonBinaryCol)
  
  return df

def encode_num_var(df, num_cols):
  scaler = StandardScaler()
  df[num_cols] = scaler.fit_transform(df[num_cols])
  
  return df
  
def encode_data(df):
  '''
  The data can be categorized as follows:
  1. Categorical features: gender, streaming tv, payment method &, etc.
  2. Numerical features  :  monthly charges, total charges
  '''
  #   Let’s convert the dependent variable 'Churn' to binary variable.(use Yes=1, No=0)
  df.loc[df.Churn == 'No','Churn'] = 0 
  df.loc[df.Churn == 'Yes','Churn'] = 1
  
  # Get the names of categorical, numerical and categorical but cardinal variables
  cat_cols, num_cols, cat_but_car = grab_col_names(df)

  # Standardize Categorical Columns
  df = encode_cat_var(df, cat_cols)

  # Standardize Numerical Columns
  df = encode_num_var(df, num_cols)

  print("\n --------------------- Information after Encoding ---------------- \n")
  print(df.info())
  print('-'*80)

  return df

def split_data(df, percentage):
  '''Split the data as per given percentage '''
  X = df.drop(['Churn','customerID'], axis=1)
  y = df['Churn']
  X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=percentage, random_state=0, stratify = y)

  return X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test

def target_var_sampling(df, X_train, y_train):
  # Plot the distribution of Target variable
  sns.countplot(x = "Churn", data = df)
  plt.xticks(fontsize = 12)
  plt.xlabel("Churn", fontsize = 20, c= "b")
  plt.ylabel("Count", fontsize = 20, c= "r")
  plt.show()

  print('-'*40)
  print("\nValue Count of Churn Variables:")
  print(df["Churn"].value_counts())
  print('-'*40)

  # To overcome class imbalance problem, we will use oversampling.
  # We should oversample solely on the training dataset, as the test dataset must be representative of the true population.
  oversample = SMOTE(random_state=0)
  X_smote, y_smote = oversample.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
  print('-'*40)
  print('After OverSampling, the shape of X_train: {}'.format(X_smote.shape))
  print('After OverSampling, the shape of y_train: {}'.format(y_smote.shape))
  print('-'*40)
  
  return X_smote, y_smote

  print('Train Accuracy Score:\t{:.2f}'.format(accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)))
  print('\nTest Accuracy Score:\t{:.2f} '.format(accuracy_score(y_test,y_test_pred)))
  print('\nROC AUC Score:\t\t{:.2f} '.format(roc_auc_score(y_test,y_test_pred)))
  print('\nPrecision:\t\t{:.2f} '.format(precision_score(y_test,y_test_pred)))
  print('\nRecall:\t\t\t{:.2f} '.format(recall_score(y_test,y_test_pred)))
  print('\nF1 Score:\t\t{:.2f} '.format(f1_score(y_test,y_test_pred)))
  print('-'*40)

def model_create(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
  models = []
  models.append(['XGBClassifier',XGBClassifier(random_state=0, learning_rate=0.1,objective='binary:logistic',eval_metric='mlogloss')])
  models.append(['RandomForest',RandomForestClassifier(random_state=0)])
  models.append(['AdaBoostClassifier',AdaBoostClassifier()])
  models.append(['GBClassifier',GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators = 50, learning_rate = 0.1, random_state=0)])
  models.append(['LGBMClassifier',LGBMClassifier(random_state=0)])
  models.append(['BaggingClassifier', BaggingClassifier(n_estimators=50, max_samples= .7, bootstrap=True, oob_score=True, random_state=22)])

  # For hybrid model preparation
  Hybrid = []
  Hybrid.append(['RidgeClassifier',RidgeClassifier()])
  Hybrid.append(['Logistic Regression',LogisticRegression(random_state=0)])
  Hybrid.append(['SVM',SVC(random_state=0)])
  Hybrid.append(['KNeigbors',KNeighborsClassifier()])
  Hybrid.append(['GaussianNB',GaussianNB()])
  Hybrid.append(['BernoulliNB',BernoulliNB()])
  Hybrid.append(['DecisionTree',DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=0)])

  # Each model performance is stored in the performance_matrix list
  model_comparision_list = []

  for m in range(len(models)):
    # performance_matrix list of this model
    performance_matrix = []
    model = models[m][1]
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred)
    accuracies = cross_val_score(estimator= model, X = X_train, y = y_train, cv=10)
    performance_matrix.append(models[m][0])
    performance_matrix.append(accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)*100)
    performance_matrix.append(accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred)*100)
    performance_matrix.append(accuracies.mean()*100)
    performance_matrix.append(accuracies.std()*100)
    performance_matrix.append(roc_auc_score(y_test,y_pred)*100)
    performance_matrix.append(precision_score(y_test,y_pred)*100)
    performance_matrix.append(recall_score(y_test,y_pred)*100)
    performance_matrix.append(f1_score(y_test,y_pred)*100)
    # Store the performance per model
    model_comparision_list.append(performance_matrix)

  hybrid_matrix = []
  Hybrid_ensemble = VotingClassifier(Hybrid)
  Hybrid_ensemble.fit(X_train,y_train)
  y_pred = Hybrid_ensemble.predict(X_test)
  y_train_pred = Hybrid_ensemble.predict(X_train)
  cm = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred)
  accuracies = cross_val_score(estimator= Hybrid_ensemble, X = X_train,y = y_train, cv=10)
  hybrid_matrix.append('Hybrid_model')
  hybrid_matrix.append(accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)*100)
  hybrid_matrix.append(accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred)*100)
  hybrid_matrix.append(accuracies.mean()*100)
  hybrid_matrix.append(accuracies.std()*100)
  hybrid_matrix.append(roc_auc_score(y_test,y_pred)*100)
  hybrid_matrix.append(precision_score(y_test,y_pred)*100)
  hybrid_matrix.append(recall_score(y_test,y_pred)*100)
  hybrid_matrix.append(f1_score(y_test,y_pred)*100)
  # Store the performance per model
  model_comparision_list.append(hybrid_matrix)

  final_perf_df = pd.DataFrame(model_comparision_list, columns=['Model','Train_Accuracy','Test_Accuracy','K-Fold Mean Accuracy','Std.Deviation','ROC_AUC','Precision','Recall','F1 Score'])

  final_perf_df.sort_values(by=['Recall','F1 Score'], inplace=True, ascending=False)
  
  print('-'*80)
  print("\nModel Performance Comparision Matrix\n")
  print('-'*80)
  print(final_perf_df)
  print('-'*80)

  return final_perf_df

# GRID SEARCH 
def tune_using_grid_search(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
  print('-'*40)
  print("\nStart GradientBoostingClassifier using GridSearch :\n")

  gb_gs = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=0)
  skfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)
  param_grid = {
                'n_estimators' : [25, 50 ,75, 100, 200],
                'learning_rate': [0.005 ,0.05, 0.5, 1.5],
                'max_depth': [2, 4, 6, 8],
                'max_features': [10, 12, 17] 
                }
  grid_gb_clf = GridSearchCV(gb_gs, param_grid, cv=skfold, scoring="recall", n_jobs= -1, verbose = 1)
  grid_gb_clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

  print('-'*40)
  print("\nBest params using grid search :\n", grid_gb_clf.best_params_)

  # Fitting GradientBoostingClassifier with best parameters.
  GBC_best = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=0, **grid_gb_clf.best_params_)

  # Fit the model 
  GBC_best.fit(X_train, y_train)

  # Predict on Train and Test
  y_pred_grid = GBC_best.predict(X_test)
  y_train_pred_grid = GBC_best.predict(X_train)

  # Evaluating Performance
  print('-'*40)
  print("\nClassifier performance using best grid search params :\n")
  evaluate_model_perf(y_test, y_pred_grid, y_train, y_train_pred_grid)

# Random Search   
def tune_using_random_search(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
  print('-'*40)
  print("\nStart GradientBoostingClassifier using RandomSearch :\n")

  gb_clf = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=0)
  skfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)
  param_grid = {
                'n_estimators' : [25, 50 ,75, 100, 200],
                'learning_rate': [0.005 ,0.05, 0.5, 1.5],
                'max_depth': [2, 4, 6, 8],
                'max_features': [10, 12, 17] 
                }
  random_gb_clf = RandomizedSearchCV(gb_clf, param_grid, cv=skfold, scoring="recall", n_jobs= -1, verbose = 1)
  random_gb_clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

  print('-'*40)
  print("\nBest params using random search :\n", random_gb_clf.best_params_)

  # Fitting classifier with new parameters
  GBC_best_Rand = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=0, **random_gb_clf.best_params_)
  GBC_best_Rand.fit(X_train, y_train)

  # Predict on Train and Test Data
  y_train_pred_random = GBC_best_Rand.predict(X_train)
  y_pred_random = GBC_best_Rand.predict(X_test)
  
  # Evaluating classifier performance
  print('-'*40)
  print("\nClassifier performance using best random search params :\n")
  evaluate_model_perf(y_test, y_pred_random, y_train, y_train_pred_random)

def finalize_model(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
  # Final Analysis
  print('-'*40)

  print("Comparing the classifier performance between base, grid search and random search, Base model is giving better Recall value. ")
  print("Also, the test and train accuracy variance is better with base model. ")
  print("We will go with base model of GB Classifier as our final model.")

  # Fit the Final model
  final_model = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators = 50, learning_rate = 0.1, random_state=0)
  final_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
  y_train_pred = final_model.predict(X_train)
  y_test_pred = final_model.predict(X_test)

  # Save best classifier as pickle file
  final_model_file = save_pickle(final_model)

  # Load for verification Purpose
  load_pickle(final_model_file)

  # Conclusion
  print('-'*40)
  print("\n\nConclusion:")
  print("\nGradientBoostingClassifier model performs the best to predict 74% customer churn.")
  print("\nObserved no improvement with tuning hyperparameters.")
  print("\nFor customer retention, month to month contract may be revisited as there is a high churn there")
  print("\nPeople who have opted for Fibre optics churn out more. Need to see the reason for the same (if Customer is not happy with this service).")
  print("\nUser who have opted for OnlineSecurity/OnlineBackup/DeviceProtection/TechCupport tend to stay. Churn is less here. Company may try to push this service to users to retain customers.")
  print("\n84% of customers who churn are not senior citizens. More information on age help us to perform better analysis and will increase the focus on particular group.")

  return final_model_file

####################### BUILD DIFEERENT MODELS AND COMPARE PERFORMANCE RESULTS ##########################
def create_compare_model(df):
  # Split the data into 80% train and 20% test. Pass test % as param
  X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = split_data(df, 0.2)

  # Target Variable Visualization and Oversampling
  X_train, y_train = target_var_sampling(df, X_train, y_train)

  final_df = model_create(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test)

  # Pick the best Model from the Data frame.
  print('-'*40)
  print("\n\nObservation:\n")
  print("GBClassifier is considerd as best model because Recall which tells how many customer churn are predicted correctly with this model.")

  # Hyperparameter tuning using Gridsearch on best model from above results
  tune_using_grid_search(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test)

  # Hyperparameter tuning using Randomsearch on best model from above results
  tune_using_random_search(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test)

  return X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test

Conclusion:

GradientBoostingClassifier model performs the best to predict 74% customer churn.

Observed no improvement with tuning hyperparameters.

For customer retention, month to month contract may be revisited as there is a high churn there

People who have opted for Fibre optics churn out more. Need to see the reason for the same (if Customer is not happy with this service).

User who have opted for OnlineSecurity/OnlineBackup/DeviceProtection/TechCupport tend to stay. Churn is less here. Company may try to push this service to users to retain customers.

84% of customers who churn are not senior citizens. More information on age help us to perform better analysis and will increase the focus on particular group.
